
To generate a firmware, run (paths may differ):

$ make
$ ./fwdecrypt R0.ROM <optional: destination path>
$ sudo ./patch-firmware.sh files . # needs sudo
$ ./fwcrypt R0.ROM <optional: source path>

After that, R0.ROM is patched and can load Rockbox.

Additionally a binary patch file named cramfs-fsl.rom.patched is created and
this file is used by Rockbox Utility to patch the firmware under the supported
platforms which would be otherwise very tricky to handle.
PLEASE NOTE: for this latter patch file to be successfully created, you SHALL
execute ALL the steps above, otherwise the patch file will be empty !

The binary patch is generated by the provided bsdiff tool and it gets compressed
(zlib algorithm) due to the fact that the diff is basically composed of zeros but
the actual byte difference.
Additionally, 4 bytes header containing the original size of the patch in big-endian
format is appended at the beginning of the compressed zlib stream. This is required
by the QByteArray::qUncompress method to correctly operate.
Eventually two additional files are created:
samsung_ypr<model>.c and samsung_ypr<model>.h.
They contain the static array of  bytes that is generated by using the bin2c tool.

rockbox.sh is a script to put into rockbox.zip. It's a small loader script
that sets stuff up.

files/lib/modules/si4709.ko is a replacement kernel module for fm radio support,
its source code is packaged in ./si4709.7z.
